This post concerns the database from Strauss on Roman shipwrecks network:

Strauss, J. (2013). Shipwrecks Database. Version 1.0. Accessed (07-12-2021) from oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/databases/shipwrecks_database/

Built from Parker, A.J. Ancient Shipwrecks of the Mediterranean and the Roman Provinces (Oxford: BAR International Series 580, 1992)

Shipwrecks Database

Andrew Wilson coordinates a catalogue of all known ancient wrecks in the Mediterranean up to 1500 AD where there is the database from Julia Strauss’s PhD thesis Roman Cargoes: Underwater Evidence from the East (London 2007).

Requirements

Install and load R packages to run the code snippets.

devtools::install_github("mplex/cedhar", subdir="pkg/sdam") # install beta v0.9.3
library("sdam") # v0.9.2 or higher
library("readxl") # read MS Excel sheets
library("networkD3") # plot interactive graphs
library("multiplex") # v2.9.8 or higher
library("multigraph") # plot valued directed graphs
# check version
packageVersion("sdam")
[1] '0.9.3'

Retrieving the Data

The Shipwrecks Database is distributed as a ZIP filesystem that needs a temporal file where to download it. The workflow below gives the steps in R with credits to this discussion.

temp <- tempfile()
download.file("http://oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/docs/StraussShipwrecks.zip", temp)

Next, we make the connection with the temporal file and unzip it with the "utils" package into object con, and because StraussShipwrecks is an MS Excel file with different sheets, we use package "readxl" to recursively read the excel sheets.

# connect temporal file and unzip excel file
con <- utils::unzip(temp, "StraussShipwrecks.xlsx")
# recursively read Excel sheets
allsheets <- sapply(readxl::excel_sheets(con), simplify=FALSE, USE.NAMES=TRUE,
            function(z) readxl::read_excel(con, sheet = z))

Before continuing with the analysis, however, we need to close the connections and remove unused files.

# close connection and garbage collection
CatchupPause <- function(Secs) {
 Sys.sleep(Secs) 
 closeAllConnections()
 gc()
 }
# close also with temporal file
unlink(temp)

Sea Areas

The shipwrecks dataset has geographical information to produce networks of relations with possible trajectories of the Roman ships. These variables are the Sea area of the shipwreck together with the network data in Place of origin and Place of destination that are columns 5, 20 and 21 in object sw.

Cleaning Data

There are, however, some record entries with extra characters like question marks, spaces, lower/upper cases, etc. that need “cleaning” for a better analysis.

# four entries to clean
sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)]
# A tibble: 4 x 3
  `Sea area`            `Place of origin` `Place of destination`       
  <chr>                 <chr>             <chr>                        
1 Adriatic              Rhodes            northern Italy               
2 Tyrrhenian Sea        Aegean.           Rome                         
3 Aegean                Cos?              Black Sea?                   
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania (?)  Brega, for trans shipment (?)

The internal function cln() in "sdam" removes special characters and capitalizes words to uniform the data. Below are four cases in the shipwreck dataset where variables Sea area, Place of origin, and Place of destination are to clean.

# default clean
sdam::cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)])
               Sea area Place of origin         Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes               northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                         Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                    Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania () Brega, for trans shipment ()
# include specific characters
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin       Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes             northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                       Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                  Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean   Tripolitania  Brega, for trans shipment 
# raise level for dots and spaces at the end
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, for trans shipment
# also capitalize words
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1)
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            Northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, For Trans Shipment

The first option removes only characters ?*+, and the second one removes also parenthesis. The command with a raised "level" removes also unnecessary spaces and dots at the end of each record, and 1 in "case" implies capitalization of just the first letter in each word.

Other entries, however, may have typo errors that need replacement:

# four entries for replacement
sw[c(632,1423,1496,1777), c(5,20:21)]

3 Western Mediterranean Marseilles        <NA>

A list of replacements for places in sw is recorded as a data frame in rptxt having two columns, one for “text to replace” and the other column for “text that replace them”.

# replace text for places
rptxt <- read.table(header=FALSE, text="
  Lll Ll
  lll ll 
  Marseilles Marseille 
  Mahgreb Maghreb 
  ")

# entries example cleaned

Network Relations

The places of origin and destination recorded in the Strauss shipwrecks dataset allows us producing a network representation of the possible trajectories of the Roman ships, and this information constitutes one kind of relation in a broader transportation system.

Edge List and Adjacency Matrix

In order to produce the network, we create first an edge list object called edgel with the two network variables in sw cleaned with the cln() options. 

# edge list cleaned and NA entries removed
edgel <- cln(sw[, 20:21], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1, na.rm=FALSE, repl=rptxt)
# head and tail of edge list
rbind(head(edgel), tail(edgel))
     Place of origin Place of destination
1              Egypt       Northern Italy
2                Cos       Northern Italy
3             Rhodes       Northern Italy
4             Aegean       Northern Italy
5               <NA>                 <NA>
6             Rhodes       Northern Italy
1779         Baetica                 <NA>
1780            <NA>                 <NA>
1781            <NA>                 <NA>
1782        Campania                 <NA>
1783            <NA>                 <NA>
1784            <NA>                 <NA>
# handle <NA> before transforming into matrix (R v4.0+)
edgel$`Place of origin`[is.na(edgel$`Place of origin`)] <- "NA"
edgel$`Place of destination`[is.na(edgel$`Place of destination`)] <- "NA"

Uses function transf() from "multiplex" to transform the edge list into the adjacency matrix of the network in array mat.

# construct matrix from edge list assuming one relation
mat <- multiplex::transf(edgel, type="toarray")
# matrix size of network
dim(mat)
[1] 162 162

Graph Representation of Shipwreck Routes

We plot the Roman Shipwrecks network as a directed graph using a force-directed layout algorithm as implemented in the R package "multigraph". The graph plotted below has labels of four hubs in the Roman shipwrecks network and different options that allows seeing the other components of the network.

# plot graph with a scope and selected labels
scp <- list(pos=0, col=66, ecol="#AFDDE9", vcol0="white", fsize=11, bg="#FFCC99")
multigraph::multigraph(mat, scope=scp, loops=TRUE, layout="force", seed=123, 
                       sel=c("Aegean","France","Luna","Rome") )

Graph of Shipwrecks Network with Four Labeled Hubs.

Plotting with "networkD3"

"networkD3" is an R package popular for producing Sankey diagrams, and which uses the capabilities of "htmlwidgets" package. It has function simpleNetwork() to be able to plot networks as ‘D3 JavaScript’ network graph allowing interactivity through a web browser. Plotting the sea regions in the Roman Shipwrecks network with this function, however, needs a data frame class object with the edge list as the input network.

To convert the ties recorded in matrix mat into an edge list format, we use transf() again but now with the "toedgel" option in the 'type' argument where edgel carries the edge list. However, some labels in mat have names separated by a comma followed by space, which is the default separator 'sep' of transf() function. This is the case, for example, of "Adriatic Via Africa, Spain, France", which means that we need to specify a tab separator in 'sep' (or another value) in order to avoid breaking labels in the edge list.

# some places in adjacency matrix
attr(mat, "dimnames")[[1]][60:62]
[1] "Cos, Crete, Italy"   "Cos, Rhodes"         "Cos, Rhodes, Athens"
# edge list with a tabulator separator
elmat <- transf(mat, type="toedgel", sep="\t")

First records in edge list where columns s, r, and t are for senders, receivers, and network ties in the data frame.

# first five entries
head(elmat)
                                   s             r t
1         Adriatic-Brindisi-Campania   Gaul, Spain 1
2 Adriatic Via Africa, Spain, France          Pisa 1
3                           Adriatic        Aegean 1
4                           Adriatic        Aegean 1
5                           Adriatic    Alexandria 1
6                           Adriatic Cyprus/Levant 1

With the edge list as elmat, we can plot the sea regions of the Roman shipwrecks network with simpleNetwork() from "networkD3" that has a 'zoom' and other options to see more easily the graph structure with a Web browser.

# zoom into a simple undirected network
networkD3::simpleNetwork(elmat, fontFamily="sans-serif", opacity=1, zoom=TRUE)

Notice that according to the output there is an isolated entity in the network. However, this is another component in the Roman Shipwrecks network having a self-relationship where NA stands for the missing information.

# last four bundles
require("magrittr")
mat %>% 
  multiplex::bundles(loops=TRUE) %>% 
  multiplex::summaryBundles() %>% 
  tail(4)
                                                          Bundles
Loop1                                       o{R} (Cyprus, Cyprus)
Loop2                                         o{R} (Italy, Italy)
Loop3                                               o{R} (NA, NA)
Loop4 o{R} (Southern Levant Or Cyprus, Southern Levant Or Cyprus)

Part of the exploratory network analysis is to look at the dyadic relations in the system, particularly if is directed like the Roman Shipwrecks network. The two functions from "multiplex" used above serve to find the different bundle patterns occurring in the network.

Largest Component

We focus on the largest component of the network, which is the second constituent in the output of comps() above. By selecting this component with argument 'sel' in function rel.sys(), we obtain the adjacency matrix of this section as an array 'type' object that is recorded in matc with has 125 nodes.

# construct adjacency matrix of largest component
matc <- multiplex::rel.sys(mat, type="toarray", sel=comps(mat)$com[[2]])
# matrix size of component
dim(matc)
[1] 125 125

There is also bundle patterns that are self-relationships.

require("magrittr")
matc %>% 
  bundles(loops=TRUE) %>% 
  summaryBundles() %>% 
  tail(2)
                  Bundles
Loop1 o{R} (Italy, Italy)
Loop2       o{R} (NA, NA)

Locations and their connections are easier to see when plotting the largest component of sea regions in the Shipwrecks network. With "multigraph":

# graph of largest component with loops and node labels
multigraph(matc, loops=TRUE, layout="force", seed=6, cex=2.5, lwd=2.5, col=8, vcol0=7, ecol=4, pos=0, fsize=7, alpha=c(1,.5))

Directed Graph of Largest Component in Roman Shipwrecks Network.

And plotting largest component of sea regions with "networkD3":

# interactive graph without zoom 
simpleNetwork(transf(matc,type="toedgel",sep="\t"), fontFamily="sans-serif", opacity=1)

Seas in the Mediterranean Basin

The two variables in edge list edgel, which are Place of origin and Place of destination, have all network locations that belong to a certain sea or region in the Mediterranean Basin or neighbouring waters. To simplify the network structure, we need to group the different places in the two network variables, and one could use for this the Sea area variable in sw. However, this variable corresponds to the shipwreck locations, which in many cases are far from the origin and destination of the ship.

The following characters serve to discern clusters of origin and destination places within Strauss Roman Shipwrecks network where most sea names are in D. Hessong cartographical map (2001) deposited in an online repository for Diplomacy information.

  • A or Æ: Aegean, including Minoan Sea
  • D: Adriatic Sea
  • I: Ionian Sea, including Ausonian Sean and Messenian Sea
  • T: Tyrrhenian Sea
  • B: Baetica, including Alboran/Iberian Sea
  • L: Ligurian Sea, including Baleares
  • E: East, from Cilician Strait through Levante Basin
  • F: Africa, including Libyan Sea and Cyrene
  • P: Punic Sea, including Berber Sea
  • C: Black Sea
  • G: Gaul
  • X: India

Because some locations entries in this dataset are vague, the clustering information for the places of origin and destination for the reduction of the network result ambiguous with entries having more than one letter.

The assignation of Sea Regions to the places of origin and destination was made by hand and are recorded in a tabular separated table in file ShipwreckSeas.txt. To load this file into object ss we need to specify the tabulator separator of the data that has a header in this case.

# read file with Mediterranean sea regions per place
ss <- read.table(file="ShipwreckSeas.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")

An excerpt of ss given below illustrates the location ambiguity in the data. For instance, Aegean And Italy in entry 8 imply three possible region seas that are Aegean, Ionian, and Adriatic; however, Aegean Rome in entry 10 implies the west coast of the Italian peninsula. In this case, the sea region corresponds to the Tyrrhenian Sea rather than the east coast facing the Adriatic.

# excerpt with 9 sea regions
ss[8:16,]
                        PLACE  CODE
8            Aegean And Italy A,D,I
9    Aegean And Lastly Cyprus   A,E
10                Aegean Rome A,T,I
11  Aegean Tripolitania Italy A,D,I
12            Aegean Via Cosa     A
13  Aegean Via Southern Italy   A,I
14              Aegean, Italy A,D,I
15              Aegean/Africa   A,F
16 Aegean/N. Africa/Propontis   A,F

Network Reduction

A clustering information serves to reduce the network into related sets of equivalent places in the system.

# matching sea regions to the edge list
ss[c(head(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3), tail(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3)),]
        PLACE CODE
73      Egypt    E
60        Cos    A
137    Rhodes    A
45   Campania    T
NA       <NA> <NA>
NA.1     <NA> <NA>

However, missing data in ss should be recorded as "NA" for future transformations.

# handle <NA> for transformation (R v4.0+)
ss$PLACE[is.na(ss$PLACE)] <- "NA"
ss$CODE[is.na(ss$CODE)] <- "NA"

Create a new edge list edgelc as data frame with sea region codes in ss, which are in new columns from and to.

# edge list with codes
edgelc <- cbind(edgel, from=ss[match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),]$CODE, 
                       to=ss[match(edgel[,2], ss$PLACE),]$CODE)
# handle <NA> before transforming into matrix (R v4.0+)
edgelc$from[is.na(edgelc$from)] <- "NA"
edgelc$to[is.na(edgelc$to)] <- "NA"
# look at last entries
tail(edgelc)

Sea Regions Origin and Destination

The adjacency matrix of letters in mat comes from columns from and to in edge list edgelc and are located in column positions 3 and 4. We extract these two columns to produce a matrix matr with ties in sea regions to plot the multigraph of the reduced structure later on.

# construct sea regions matrix

Aggregation of Sea Regions in the Mediterranean Basin

Further aggregation of the Sea Regions in the Mediterranean Basin is possible by grouping them where a number is given to geographical regions in the Mediterranean Basin:

  •   1:   West
  •   2:   East
  • 21:   East-West
  • 12:   West-East (also when West and East are tied)
  •   3:   Far East
  •   0:    NA

First, we take from ss the sea regions codes in component CODE and group them by hand.

Timespans of Existence and Relative Dating

A temporal span or timespan of existence ττ is a temporal stage or time block in a range of time ΩΩ of the distance between two boundaries of existence, a “limit before which” and a “limit after which”.

Time blocks aa and bb are finite and they stand for the “before-” and “after which” ττ, respectively, which implies that any timespan is natural ordered related between time blocks aa and bb.

a≤τ≤ba≤τ≤b

When the three temporal stages in percentages are known, which means they are finite, each time block is calculated as 100 minus the sum of the other stages

a=100−(b+τ).τ=100−(a+b).b=100−(a+τ).a=100−(b+τ).τ=100−(a+b).b=100−(a+τ).

This arrangement of time blocks in the order of their occurrence constitutes a chronology with a timeline that looks like:

Time Variables in Shipwreck Data

There are variables in the Roman shipwrecks dataset related to time and dating. For instance, variables 'Earliest date' and 'Latest date' serve to delimit the timespans of existence of the shipwreck record. Other two time related variables having data are 'Period' and 'Dating', while variables "Date range", "Mid point of date range", and "Probability" do not contain any data in sw. However, these two variables can be calculated from the available timespans of existence.

Aoristic Sum: Probability of existence of shipwrecks

There are different ways to estimate probabilities of existence of artefacts in the shipwrecks dataset.

For instance, the aoristic sum is a proxy to compute the probability of existence of archaeological artefacts such as shipwrecks. Below is the aoristic sum of the shipwrecks dataset that is computed by function prex() per century as specified in argument 'bins' with the visualization afterwards as bar plots.

# plot aoristic sum per 100 years
require("magrittr")
sw %>% 
  sdam::prex(vars=c("Earliest date", "Latest date"), bins=100) %>% 
  barplot(main="Aoristic Sum Shipwrecks Dataset (100 year bins)")

Aoristic Sum Shipwrecks Dataset (100 year bins)

There are in total 50 time blocks in the range of time of the shipwreck dataset; however, some shipwrecks may belong neither to the Hellenistic nor to the Roman period as we can see in the barplot. In order to delimitate the probability of existence results, we may need to look at a periodisation in history with chronological phases of the Mediterranean.

Distributions of Shipwrecks

Most of the shipwrecks in the database are from the Archaic to Middle Venetian, which is from 700 BC until AD 1600, and for the Byzantine period until AD 1200. According to the Mediterranean chronology phases, the Hellenistic and the Roman periods are from 325 BC to AD 650. If we consider the aoristic sum of shipwrecks from these later two periods, we end up with the following barplot.

# plot positions 26 to 37 in output for Hellenistic and Roman periods
require("magrittr")
sw %>% 
prex(vars=c("Earliest date", "Latest date"), bins=100) %>% 
  .[26:37] %>% 
  barplot(ylim=c(0,1000))

Aoristic Sum per Century for Hellenistic and Roman Periods

The number of bins affects the shape of the distribution and, for instance, using 200 year bins the distribution has a relative stability stage from 200 BC to AD 200.

# Hellenistic and Roman periods now in positions 13 to 19
require("magrittr")
sw %>% 
  prex(vars=c("Earliest date", "Latest date"), bins=200) %>% 
  .[13:19] %>% 
  barplot(ylim=c(0,2500))

Aoristic Sum for Hellenistic and Roman Periods with 200 year bins.

Density estimate

Adding a kernel density (KD) estimate for a distribution requires the use of histograms for count data. Below there is an histogram of the distribution of shipwrecks together with a normal (or Gaussian) approximation curve and a kernel density line of the distribution.

Aoristic Sum with normal kernel smooth.

Changing Resolution and Range

The aoristic sum is also calculated with different bins other than as per century. For instance, years from BC 600 to AD 400 are positions 97 to 136 in the aoristic sum range of shipwrecks in sw with bins to 25 years.

# plot aoristic sum per 25 years
require("magrittr")
sw %>% 
  sdam::prex(vars=c("Earliest date", "Latest date"), bins=25) %>%

Four centuries

To split the network into the first three common era centuries, we need take the mid points in x as median normalization values given by prex() as Mid point.

# mid point dates in shipwrecks
tmp <- prex(sw, type="mp", vars=c("Earliest date","Latest date"))$`Mid point`

 [1]     NA    0.0    0.0  -87.5  100.5 1250.0 1250.0  150.0 1250.0 1250.0   37.5  125.0  450.0
[14] 1250.0  -50.5 1150.0  400.0

Century time intervals of the shipwreck dataset with mid points are identified by Roman numerals with a character data type and they are recorded in swmpc.

# 100 year bins until max value
require("magrittr")
swmpc <- 
  findInterval(tmp, seq(0, max(tmp,na.rm=TRUE), by=100), all.inside=FALSE)  %>% 
  utils::as.roman() %>% 
  as.character()

By considering only common era years for centuries, all BC years with negative dates become <NA>. However, the not available entries in swmpc are a mixture of missing information and before common era years.

# some records as centuries

  noquote()
 [1] <NA> I    I    I    I    I    I    <NA> II   <NA> VI

Before Common Era

For years before common era or years BC, there is a special workflow for creating network data. Start by finding the positions of all "BC" mid point dates in swmpc to retrieve the BC years in the mid points previously recorded in tmp, and where atmp stands for the absolute values of the BC years.

# how many BC dates?
require("magrittr")
which(swmpc%in%c('BC')) %>% 
  length()
[1] 661
# mid points BC years as absolute dates
require("magrittr")
atmp <- 
  tmp[which(swmpc%in%c('BC'))] %>% 
  abs()
# last mid points of negative dates
tail(atmp)
[1]   2.5 350.0 187.5  50.5  87.5  50.5

atmp has any missing data.

Then record in yearBC all BC centuries as Roman numerals with absolute values.

# use absolute value for BC
require("magrittr")
yearBC <-

Plotting temporal networks

For the plotting of the shipwrecks dataset as temporal networks, create a scope for a valued graph with self-relationships and characteristics of nodes and edges.

# scope temporal networks
scps <- list(valued=TRUE, loops=TRUE, cex=2, pos=0, col="#FFCC00", ecol="#AFDDE9", 
             vcol0="white", fsize=7, hds=.5, vedist=-4)

Since many of the places in the shipwrecks dataset are undefined, the node in the valued graph representing missing information has a very wide self-edge, and the plotting of the graph requires loop scaling for a better visualization.

Saeculum I Ante

# loop scale 10 pct
multigraph(mtIBC, scope=scps, values=TRUE, layout="force", seed=3, lscl=.1, main="Saeculum I ante commune era")

Saeculum I

# loop scale 5 pct
multigraph(mtI, scope=scps, values=TRUE, layout="force", seed=8, lscl=.05, main="Saeculum I")

Saeculum II

# loop scale 10 pct
multigraph(mtII, scope=scps, values=TRUE, layout="force", seed=1, lscl=.1, main="Saeculum II")

Saeculum III

# loop scale 5 pct
multigraph(mtIII, scope=scps, values=TRUE, layout="force", seed=5, lscl=.05, main="Saeculum III")

Aggregation Saeculum I ante

For the first century BC, the adjacency matrix with regional maritime routes are obtained by matching edge lists with components PLACE and CODE in ss with origin and destination places in swBC. These two vectors are then binded with the cargo variables into the new data frame swBCc from which the aggregated adjacency matrix matBCr is created.

# columns 2-8 for places origin/destination and cargo variables
swBCc <- cbind(swBC[,2:8], from=ss[match(swBC[,2], ss$PLACE),]$CODE, 
                           to=ss[match(swBC[,3], ss$PLACE),]$CODE)

Match from ssg, which binds the names of the shipwreck places with their groups, in order to add to swBCc the regional groups in swBCr the origin and destination places as fra and til during the first century before common era.

# I cent. BC regional groups
